window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"You are provided with three retort stands, a pendulum bob, drawing board, stop-watch and other necessary apparatus. Using the diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions:  (i) Fix the drawing paper on the drawing board and hold the board with two clamps such that its vertical.  (ii) Suspend the pendulum bob such that it hangs freely in front of the drawing appear.  (iii) Draw a line  RP  representing the rest position of the pendulum string and mark the position  P  of the centre of the pendulum bob at rest.  (iv) Displace the pendulum bob to one side in a plane parallel to the drawing board.  (v) Mark the new position  P1  of the centre of the bob.  (vi) Measure and record the perpendicular distance,  d  of  P1  from the line  RP .  (vii) Evaluate and record  d2 .  (viii) Measure and record the vertical height  h  of  P1  above  P .  (ix) Evaluate G = d2h\\frac{d^{2}}{h}hd2\u200b  (x) Repeat the procedure for  four  other oppositions of  P1   (xi) Tabulate your readings.  (xii) Remove the drawing board so that the pendulum bob can swing freely.  (xiii) Set the pendulum bob oscillating through a small amplitude and determine the time  t  for 20 oscillations  (xiv) Determine and record the period,  T .   (xv) Plot a graph with  G  on the vertical axis and  h  on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0, 0).  (xvi) Determine the intercept  I  on the horizontal axis.  (xvii) Evaluate A = I19.7T2\\frac{I}{19.7T^{2}}19.7T2I\u200b  (xviii) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    d(cm)d2(cm2)h(cm)G = d2h\\frac{d^{2}}{h}hd2\u200b (cm)t(sec)T = t20\\frac{t}{20}20t\u200b(sec)17.50306.255.7053.7320.001.05012.50156.254.7038.2420.001.05011.40129.963.8034.2020.001.0503.9015.212.4016.3420.001.0503.3.010.891.606.8020.001.050        Intercept, I = 0.94 cm    T = 1.050 seconds    A = I19.7T2\\frac{I}{19.7T^{2}}19.7T2I\u200b = 119.7\u00d71.052\\frac{1}{19.7\u00d71.05^{2}}19.7\u00d71.0521\u200b = 0.046 cm/sec2    Precautions:  1. I ensured conical oscillation was avoided to maintain a consistent, linear motion during the experiment.    2. I conducted the experiment in a draft-free environment to prevent any air currents from affecting the oscillation.    3. I minimized parallax error by positioning my eye level with the meter rule and stopwatch scales while taking readings.    4. I identified and corrected any zero error on the stopwatch and meter rule to ensure accurate measurements.    5. I made sure all traces and markings were clear and precise to facilitate accurate tracking and measurement.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"Distinguish between the period and frequency of oscillation of a simple pendulum. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The period of oscillation of a simple pendulum is the time taken for the pendulum to complete one full oscillation (swing), usually measured in seconds. In contrast, the frequency is the number of oscillations the pendulum completes per unit time, usually measured in hertz (Hz). Period and frequency are inversely related; as the period increases, the frequency decreases, and vice versa.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"MOTION : TYPES OF MOTION","question":"Differentiate between oscillatory and rotational motions. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Oscillatory motion is a type of motion in which an object moves back and forth about a fixed point or equilibrium position, such as a pendulum swinging or a mass on a spring. This motion is periodic and usually follows a specific path within a limited range.    Rotational motion, on the other hand, occurs when an object spins or rotates around a fixed axis, such as a wheel turning or a planet orbiting its axis. In rotational motion, every point on the object moves in a circular path around the axis, and the object completes continuous cycles without necessarily returning to an equilibrium position.    In summary, oscillatory motion involves periodic back-and-forth movement, while rotational motion involves continuous spinning around a central axis.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a glass block, plane mirror and optical pins.  (i) Place the glass block on a drawing sheet and trace its outline ABCD as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Remove the block, measure and record the width W of the block.  (iii) Draw a normal ON to DC at a point about one-quarter the length of DC.  (iv) Draw a line making an angle  i  = 10\u00b0 with the normal.  (v) Replace the block on its outline and mount the plane mirror vertically behind the block such that it makes good contact with the face AB.  (vi) Stick two pins P1 and P2 on the line MO.  (vii) Looking through the face CD, stick two other pins P3 and P4 such that they appear to be in a straight line with the images of pins P1 and P2 seen through the block.  (viii) Join P3 and P4 with straight lien and extend it to touch the face CD at O1  (ix) Draw a perpendicular line from the midpoint of OO1 to meet AB at Q.  (x) Draw lines OQ1, O1Q and normal O1 , N1 produced.  (xi) Measure and record \u03b8 , e and d.  (xii) Evaluate m = sin e and n = cos (\u03b82\\frac{\u03b8}{2}2\u03b8\u200b)  (xiii) Repeat the procedure for  i  = 20\u00b0, 30\u00b0, 40\u00b0 and 50\u00b0.  (xiv) Tabulate your readings.  (xv) Plot a graph with  m  on the vertical axis and  n  on the horizontal axis.  (xvi) Determine the slope, s of the graph and evaluate \u03b8 = 2Ws .  (xvii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    W = 4.90 cm    io\u03b8ed (cm)m = sin en = cos (n2\\frac{n}{2}2n\u200b)1052405.000.64280.89882052405.000.55920.9272304029.503.500.49240.93974053385.200.61570.89495048344.200.55920.9135        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.6125\u22120.53750.9\u22120.925\\frac{0.6125-0.5375}{0.9-0.925}0.9\u22120.9250.6125\u22120.5375\u200b = 0.075\u22120.025\\frac{0.075}{-0.025}\u22120.0250.075\u200b = -3    \u03b8 = 2Ws = 2 \u00d7 4.9 \u00d7 (-3) = -29.4    Precautions:  1. I ensured all traces were clear and precise to facilitate accurate measurement.  2. I positioned the pins vertically to avoid misalignment and ensured consistent readings.  3. I placed the pins with sufficient spacing to maintain accuracy in positioning and prevent overlap.  4. I avoided parallax error by viewing the protractor and meter rule directly at eye level when taking measurements.  5. I secured all apparatus firmly to prevent any movement that could alter readings during the experiment.  6. I performed the experiment in a stable environment, free from vibrations or drafts, to prevent unintended disturbances.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Explain the term  refractive index  and give a mathematical expression for it in terms of wavelength. [2marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The refractive index of a material is a measure of how much the material slows down light relative to its speed in a vacuum. It indicates the bending or refraction of light as it passes from one medium into another.    Mathematically, the refractive index n is given by:    n = \u03bb0\u03bbm\\frac{\u03bb_{0}}{\u03bb_{m}}\u03bbm\u200b\u03bb0\u200b\u200b    where:  \u03bb0 is the wavelength of light in a vacuum, and  \u03bbm is the wavelength of light in the material.    This relationship shows that as light enters a denser medium, its wavelength decreases, resulting in a higher refractive index.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the conditions necessary for total internal reflection to occur for a given pair of media. [2marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. The light must be travelling from a denser medium to a less dense medium.  2. The angle of incidence in the denser medium must be greater than the critical angle.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a voltmeter V, a chemical cell/battery E, two standard resistors R1 and R2, a potentiometer AB, a key K, a jockey and other necessary materials.  (i) Set up a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Close the key K.  (iii) Make contact with the potentiometer wire AB using the jockey at a point C such that AC = x = 20 cm.  (iv) Read and record the voltmeter reading, V.  (v) Evaluate x-1 and V-1.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for other values of x = 30, 40, 50, 60 and 80 cm.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with V-1 on the vertical axis and x-1 on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0, 0).  (ix) Determine the:  (A) slope, s, of the graph;  (B) intercept, c on the vertical axis.  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    S/Nx(cm)V(V)x-1(cm-1)V-1(V-1)120.003.330.0500.30230.002.500.0330.40340.002.000.0250.50450.001.670.0200.60560.001.430.0170.70680.001.110.0130.90         slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.8\u22120.30.01\u22120.045\\frac{0.8-0.3}{0.01-0.045}0.01\u22120.0450.8\u22120.3\u200b = 0.5\u22120.035\\frac{0.5}{-0.035}\u22120.0350.5\u200b = -14.29    Intercept, c = 0.95    Precautions:  1. I ensured all connections were tight and terminals were clean to maintain consistent current flow.    2. I ensured readings were only taken when the key was inserted, to prevent interruptions in the circuit.    3. I avoided parallax error by aligning my eye directly with the scale when reading the voltmeter and meter rule.    4. I identified and corrected any zero error on the voltmeter and meter rule to ensure accurate measurements.    5. I carefully placed the jockey on the wire without dragging it to avoid wear on the wire and maintain contact accuracy.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY~~ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"State two devices in which Ohm's law does not apply. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Ohm's law does not apply in the following devices:    1. Diodes: These semiconductor devices allow current to flow in one direction only and exhibit a non-linear current-voltage relationship.    2. Transistors: These devices are used for amplification and switching, and their behavior is not linear; they do not obey Ohm's law under all conditions.    3. Thermistors: These are temperature-sensitive resistors, where resistance changes significantly with temperature, leading to non-linear behavior.    4. Superconductors: In certain conditions, superconductors exhibit zero resistance, meaning Ohm's law does not apply.    5. Non-linear Resistors: Resistors that have a resistance that changes with the applied voltage or current, such as varistors, do not follow Ohm's law.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2010>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2010","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"A current of 1 A is supplied to two resistors of resistances 2 \u03a9 and 3 \u03a9 connected in parallel. Calculate the current in each resistor. [2 marks]    (Provide your answers to 1 d.p, with the units and in this form: current of the 2 \u03a9 resistor, current of the 3 \u03a9 resistor e.g 1.2 m, 2.3 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"We first find the effective resistance of the circuit:    1RT\\frac{1}{R_{T}}RT\u200b1\u200b = 1R1\\frac{1}{R_{1}}R1\u200b1\u200b + 1R2\\frac{1}{R_{2}}R2\u200b1\u200b    1RT\\frac{1}{R_{T}}RT\u200b1\u200b  = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b + 13\\frac{1}{3}31\u200b = 56\\frac{5}{6}65\u200b    RT = 65\\frac{6}{5}56\u200b = 1.2 \u03a9    The voltage across the 1.2 \u03a9 resistor is:    V = IRT = 1 &#215; 1.2 = 1.2 V    Since the voltage across RT is the same as both the 2 \u03a9 and 3 \u03a9 since the two are in parallel:    The current across the 2 \u03a9 will be:    I = VR\\frac{V}{R}RV\u200b = 1.22\\frac{1.2}{2}21.2\u200b = 0.6 A    The current across the 3 \u03a9 will be:    I = VR\\frac{V}{R}RV\u200b = 1.23\\frac{1.2}{3}31.2\u200b = 0.4 A","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"}];